  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Rapid Response Humanitarian Assistance to IDPs in N. and Central Iraq</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="3">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">IDPs</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="4">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mercy Corps proposes a &#x2018;rapid response&#x2019; humanitarian assistance intervention of four months to provide direct assistance to an estimated 3,000 IDP families (18,000 individuals) in north and central Iraq. The program intervention areas will cover four governorates, focusing on the geographical reach of six local partners in Diyala, Kirkuk, Salah-al Din, and Ninewa.
 The selected partners will be &#x2018;on call&#x2019; to rapidly respond to urgently identified needs within their specific geographical area. The local partner will be assigned a Mercy Corps &#x2018;field focal point&#x2019;. When any newly displaced families arrive in their geographical area, the partner will place a call to their field focal point providing four key pieces of information; (1) where they are located; (2) how many people; (3) what is their shelter status (i.e. where are they being hosted); (4) what is their most urgent need. The field focal point will immediately initiate the rapid response mechanism to mobilize the necessary resources &#x2013; through Mercy Corps&#x2019; existing operations and programs teams &#x2013; to distribute appropriate assistance either by dispatching in-kind NFI kits or a hawala cash transfer for the partner to distribute. Where the most urgent identified need cannot be met by Mercy Corps assistance, Mercy Corps senior staff will engage in the OCHA / inter-agency coordination mechanism to refer the case to the appropriate agency. For example food needs to the World Food Program (WFP) and disability issues to Handicap International.</narrative>
  </description>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Mercy Corps will reach an estimated 3,000 IDP families (18,000 individuals1) in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq (KR-I) and disputed and occupied territories through a &#x2018;rapid response&#x2019; mechanism for the provision of non-food items (NFIs) and cash. This project is an expansion of an existing internally displaced persons (IDP) program currently being implemented by Mercy Corps Iraq.</narrative>
  </description>
